            <div class="mainBodyText">
                <span class="fs5"><!-- OldURL: http://boards2.parentsplace.com/messages/get/pplibchristiann15/22/1.html -->
<p>Hi, Carrie.  Have one of Cynthia's cyber-latte's. There may even be ...</p>

some of Jennifer's bread pudding left. 
<P>

I'm thinking Tom Harpur might be a pleasant read for you. Madeleine L'Engle might be another. I've never read either from your perspective, though. Having come from a atheist background, I was blissfully spared most of the Sunday School shallowness that gets inflicted on children and literalists. When I read Julian of Norwich, I'm able to glory in the abstract symbolism without stumbling over any of the medaeival catholic baggage. You might not be so lucky. 
<P>

If you try reading the bible, get one with *Oxford* study notes. Oxford is the home of the textual criticism school of bible studies. They treat the bible as a historical text, identifying where the glosses are, and comparing and contrasting the claims of the text to external sources. It's a lot easier to take the Bible if you assume it was written by ordinary people who had their own human agendas and limited understanding, and wrote from their own perspective. Textual criticism helps you form that understanding, and being supported by scholars from the English-speaking worlds oldest and most prestigious university doesn't hurt.
<P>

Feel free to hang around, too. We have other recovering fundamentalists here. Somewhere, there's a link to the personal-creed-writing exercise that we did three years ago. You'll see there that few of us believe in the concrete God-meme that most atheists don't believe in. For that matter, few of us believe in the same way at all, though we manage to "unity of the Spirit through the bond of peace." We tend to have a running bible study in one form or another as well, which tends to be radicall different from those Thomsan-Chain-Reference sixty-minutes-to-a-verse acceptable-interpretations-only-please studies that infest "Bible-believing" congregations. 
<P>

And there's great cyber-snacks on every board. So make yourself at home.

<P>

</span>
